Post Doctoral Fellow Position
Dalhousie University
Nova Scotia Math Circles and the Department of Mathematics and Statistics

Nova Scotia Math Circles and the Department of Mathematics and
Statistics at Dalhousie University are advertising a post-doctoral
fellowship with duties in outreach, outreach coordination, and
communication.

The post-doctoral fellow will spend 50% of their duties on research,
and 50% on outreach and outreach coordination, see job description
below.

The academic supervisor of the PDF must be a member of the department
of Mathematics and Statistics at Dalhousie University. Interested
candidates should contact their proposed supervisor before the
application.

The outreach coordinator duties consist of the following:

* Communicate with teachers and schoolboards
* Organize outreach trips to schools in the province
* Coordinate regular staff and casuals for school visits and outreach
   events
* Maintain the Math Circles finances
* Work with external relations and sponsors
* Ensure continued funding for Math Circles as required

The outreach coordinator should have received their PhD after July
2013 and before August 2017. They should have strong research skills,
an interest in math outreach, good social and organizational skills,
and experience in outreach as well as outreach and/or event
coordination.

Advantageous but not necessary are the following: experience with html
and design programs, a driver???s license, and experience in fundraising
with corporations.

Terms of employment will conform to post-doctoral fellowship positions
at Dalhousie University. The position is for one year, starting August
2017. The position is renewable for a second year subject to budgetary
approval.

For more information on Nova Scotia Math Circles, see
http://www.nsmathcircles.com/

To apply, please send the following:

* A cover letter, including the name of the proposed supervisor
* A CV (which includes relevant experience on outreach and organization)
* A teaching dossier with an emphasis on outreach
* A brief research statement
* A minimum of three reference letters: two on research and at least
   one, but preferably two, on outreach and administrative experience.

This should be sent before March 15, 2017 via email to Queena
Crooker-Smith at queena.smith@dal.ca





[For admin and other information see: http://www.mta.ca/~cat-dist/ ]

